Design a data structure that supports insertion of elements and removal of all occurrences of a given element while printing the remaining elements in their original insertion order.

-> Problem Statement
We need to design a data structure that supports the following operations:
a. add(int x) : Adds an integer x to the data structure.
b. removeAndPrint(int x): Removes all occurrences of x from the data structure and prints the remaining elements in the same order as they were inserted.
Example:
Input:
add(10), add(20), add(10), add(30), removeAndPrint(10)
add(30), add(40), add(60), removeAndPrint(30)
Output:
20 30
20 40 60

-> Using ArrayList vs LinkedList
We can use ArrayList or LinkedList to implement this data structure. Below is a comparison:
  -> ArrayList Approach:
  a. Add Operation: O(1) (Amortized Time Complexity)
  b.RemoveAndPrint Operation: O(n) (Since shifting is required after removal)
  
  -> LinkedList Approach (Preferred Solution):
  a. Add Operation: O(1) (Worst case as well)
  b. RemoveAndPrint Operation: O(n) (Efficient with iterators)
Since LinkedList allows fast insertions and removals using iterators, it is an optimal choice.

Implementation Using LinkedList
Below is a Java implementation using LinkedList:

import java.util.*;
​class MyDS {
    LinkedList<Integer> list = new LinkedList<>();
    
    void add(int x) {
        list.add(x);
    }
    
    void removeAndPrint(int x) {
        Iterator<Integer> it = list.iterator();
        
        while (it.hasNext()) {
            Integer n = it.next();
            if (n.equals(x)) {
                it.remove();
            } else {
                System.out.print(n + " ");
            }
        }
        System.out.println();
    }
}
​
public class GFG {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        MyDS ds = new MyDS();
        
        ds.add(10);
        ds.add(20);
        ds.add(10);
        ds.add(30);
        ds.removeAndPrint(10); 
        
        ds.add(30);
        ds.add(40);
        ds.add(60);
        ds.removeAndPrint(30); 
    }
}


Output:
20 30
20 40 60

Explanation of Code
1. Class MyDS:
a. Uses a LinkedList to store integers.
b. add(int x) appends an integer to the list.
c. removeAndPrint(int x) iterates through the list, removes x, and prints the remaining elements.

2. Class GFG (Main Class):
a. Demonstrates adding and removing elements.
b. Prints the updated list after each removeAndPrint() operation.

-> Complexity Analysis
    Operation          Time Complexity
    add(x)	           O(1) (Worst case)
    removeAndPrint(x)	 O(n)
a. Adding elements is O(1) because LinkedList allows quick appends.
b.Removing elements is O(n) since we traverse using an iterator.
